	Abstract = {We show that gamma-ray burst (GRB) afterglow observations strongly suggest, within the fireball model framework, that radiating electrons are shock accelerated to a power-law energy distribution, dne/dgammae~gamma-pe, with universal index p~2.2, and that the fraction of shock energy carried by electrons, xie, is universal and close to equipartition, xie~1/3. For universal p and xie, a single measurement of the X-ray afterglow flux on the timescale of a day provides a robust estimate of the fireball energy per unit solid angle, ε, averaged over a conical section of the fireball of opening angle theta~0.1. The energy estimate ε varies by ~50% as p is modified over the range of values p=2.2+/-0.2 typically inferred from observations. Applying our analysis to BeppoSAX afterglow data, we find that (1) fireball energies are in the range of 4piε=1051.5-1053.5 ergs; (2) the ratio of observed gamma-ray to total fireball energy per unit solid angle, εgamma/ε, is of order unity, satisfying |log10(εgamma/ ε)|<~0.5 and (3) if fireballs are jet-like, their opening angle should satisfy theta>~0.1. Our results imply that if typical opening angles are theta~0.1, a value consistent with our analysis, the total energy associated with a GRB event is in the range of 1050-1051.5 ergs.},
